To track a user's location without requiring explicit permission, you can use the HTML5 Geolocation API. This API allows you to access the user's location data, but it does require the user to grant permission. However, there are ways to prompt the user for permission in a non-intrusive manner. Here's a simple example of how you can implement this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Track User Location</title>
</head>
<body>
    <button onclick="getLocation()">Get Location</button>
    <p id="demo"></p>

    <script>
        function getLocation() {
            if (navigator.geolocation) {
                navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(showPosition);
            } else {
                document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "Geolocation is not supported by this browser.";
            }
        }

        function showPosition(position) {
            var lat = position.coords.latitude;
            var lon = position.coords.longitude;
            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "Latitude: " + lat + "<br>Longitude: " + lon;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, a button is provided for the user to click to get their location. When the button is clicked, the `getLocation` function is called, which checks if the browser supports the Geolocation API. If it does, it calls the `getCurrentPosition` method, which prompts the user for permission to access their location. If the user grants permission, the `showPosition` function is called with the user's latitude and longitude.

This approach ensures that the user is aware that their location is being accessed and gives them the option to grant or deny permission.
